'''Tenpaku Faith''' (天白信仰) is a form of {{ill|folk religion|ja|民間信仰|12=draft|12=draft}} found primarily in the eastern half of {{ill|Honshū|ja|本州|12=draft|12=draft}}. Its distribution centers on {{ill|Nagano Prefecture|ja|長野県|12=draft|12=draft}} and {{ill|Shizuoka Prefecture|ja|静岡県|12=draft|12=draft}}, extending southward to the Nansei and Shima regions of {{ill|Mie Prefecture|ja|三重県|12=draft|12=draft}} and northward to {{ill|Iwate Prefecture|ja|岩手県|12=draft|12=draft}}.

Due to the diverse associations with {{ill|star deities|ja|星神|12=draft|12=draft}}, [[Suijin|water gods]], and prayers for safe childbirth, various studies and interpretations have been conducted. Since the 1980s, the faith has often been linked to the ancestral deity of the {{ill|Asami clan|ja|麻積氏|12=draft|12=draft}}, Tenpakuhahajin (天白羽神, also known as {{ill|Nagashirahahajin|ja|長白羽神|12=draft|12=draft}}), worshipped at the {{ill|Hashiro Shrine|ja|機殿神社|12=draft|12=draft}} in the ancient province of Ise.

== History of Research ==
Shun'ichirō Mitoshi noted that the earliest studies on Tenpaku faith date back to the {{ill|Edo period|ja|江戸時代|12=draft|12=draft}}. In the linguistic dictionary *Wakun no Shiori* compiled by {{ill|Tanikawa Kotosuga|ja|谷川士清|12=draft|12=draft}}, there is a reference to "numerous shrines in Ise Province called Tenpaku Daimyōjin, though their exact nature is unclear." Similarly, *Chōshū Fushi* mentions the Tenpaku Shrine in Ōya Village (now {{ill|Ōya Town|ja|大矢町|12=draft|12=draft}} in {{ill|Inazawa City|ja|稲沢市|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Aichi Prefecture|ja|愛知県|12=draft|12=draft}}), suggesting it was dedicated to {{ill|Venus|ja|金星|12=draft|12=draft}}, referred to as Taibakusei (太白星). In 1862, Takahira Nakamura theorized in *Suruga Shiryō* that the deity might represent a synthesis of Tianyi (天一) and Taibai (太白) deities.

In 1909, the folklorist {{ill|Yanagita Kunio|ja|柳田國男|12=draft|12=draft}} explored Tenpaku in *Life of the Mountain People*. In subsequent works, he dismissed earlier speculative theories, proposing that Tenpaku was likely connected to {{ill|wind deities|ja|風神|12=draft|12=draft}}. This theory gained significant attention among later scholars.

From the post-World War II period, research on Tenpaku progressed. {{ill|Yoshio Horita|ja|堀田吉雄|12=draft|12=draft}}, a disciple of Yanagita, published several studies between 1951 and 1964. While he leaned toward the theory of Tenpaku being a fusion of Chinese deities Tianyi and Taibai, he remained cautious, awaiting further evidence.

In 1971, Nokiku Imai compiled a detailed map of Tenpaku shrines in *Great Tenpaku Kami*, asserting that the faith predates wet-rice cultivation and reaches back to the {{ill|Jōmon period|ja|縄文時代|12=draft|12=draft}}. The publication also included analyses suggesting connections to {{ill|flood control|ja|風水害|12=draft|12=draft}}, Tibetan Lamaist sexual symbolism, and the deity Tenpakuhahajin.

Building on Imai's research, Sōmoku Yamada conducted in-depth surveys in five prefectures (Mie, Aichi, Nagano, Shizuoka, and Yamanashi), which he serialized as *Tenpaku Chronicles* in 1977. He proposed that Tenpaku's origins lie in the deity Tenpakuhahajin.

