[[sn:Tenpaku faith]] [[en:Tenpaku faith]] [[ja:天白信仰]] [[sn:enpaku faith]]

'''Tenpaku Faith''' (天白信仰) is a form of {{ill|folk religion|ja|民間信仰|qq=draft|qq=draft}} found primarily in the eastern half of {{ill|Honshū|ja|本州|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. Its distribution centers on {{ill|Nagano Prefecture|ja|長野県|qq=draft|qq=draft}} and {{ill|Shizuoka Prefecture|ja|静岡県|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, extending southward to the Nansei and Shima regions of {{ill|Mie Prefecture|ja|三重県|qq=draft|qq=draft}} and northward to {{ill|Iwate Prefecture|ja|岩手県|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.
Due to the diverse associations with {{ill|star deities|ja|星神|1=Worship of heavenly bodies|2=ja|3=星神|lt=Star deities|1=Worship of heavenly bodies|2=ja|3=星神|lt=Star deities|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, [[Suijin|water gods]], and prayers for safe childbirth, various studies and interpretations have been conducted. Since the 1980s, the faith has often been linked to the ancestral deity of the {{ill|Asami clan|ja|麻積氏|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, Tenpakuhahajin (天白羽神, also known as {{ill|Nagashirahahajin|ja|長白羽神|qq=draft|qq=draft}}), worshipped at the {{ill|Hashiro Shrine|ja|機殿神社|qq=draft|qq=draft}} in the ancient province of Ise.
== History of Research == Shun'ichirō Mitoshi noted that the earliest studies on Tenpaku faith date back to the {{ill|Edo period|ja|江戸時代|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. In the linguistic dictionary *Wakun no Shiori* compiled by {{ill|Tanikawa Kotosuga|ja|谷川士清|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, there is a reference to "numerous shrines in Ise Province called Tenpaku Daimyōjin, though their exact nature is unclear." Similarly, *Chōshū Fushi* mentions the Tenpaku Shrine in Ōya Village (now {{ill|Ōya Town|ja|大矢町|qq=draft|qq=draft}} in {{ill|Inazawa City|ja|稲沢市|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Aichi Prefecture|ja|愛知県|qq=draft|qq=draft}}), suggesting it was dedicated to {{ill|Venus|ja|金星|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, referred to as Taibakusei (太白星). In 1862, Takahira Nakamura theorized in *Suruga Shiryō* that the deity might represent a synthesis of Tianyi (天一) and Taibai (太白) deities.
In 1909, the folklorist {{ill|Yanagita Kunio|ja|柳田國男|qq=draft|qq=draft}} explored Tenpaku in *Life of the Mountain People*. In subsequent works, he dismissed earlier speculative theories, proposing that Tenpaku was likely connected to {{ill|wind deities|ja|風神|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. This theory gained significant attention among later scholars.
From the post-World War II period, research on Tenpaku progressed. {{ill|Yoshio Horita|ja|堀田吉雄|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, a disciple of Yanagita, published several studies between 1951 and 1964. While he leaned toward the theory of Tenpaku being a fusion of Chinese deities Tianyi and Taibai, he remained cautious, awaiting further evidence.
In 1971, Nokiku Imai compiled a detailed map of Tenpaku shrines in *Great Tenpaku Kami*, asserting that the faith predates wet-rice cultivation and reaches back to the {{ill|Jōmon period|ja|縄文時代|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. The publication also included analyses suggesting connections to {{ill|flood control|ja|風水害|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, Tibetan Lamaist sexual symbolism, and the deity Tenpakuhahajin.
Building on Imai's research, Sōmoku Yamada conducted in-depth surveys in five prefectures (Mie, Aichi, Nagano, Shizuoka, and Yamanashi), which he serialized as *Tenpaku Chronicles* in 1977. He proposed that Tenpaku's origins lie in the deity Tenpakuhahajin.
== Places Associated with Tenpaku == {{Seealso|{{ill|Tenpaku|ja|天白|qq=draft|qq=draft}}}} === Aichi Prefecture === * {{ill|Tenpaku River (Aichi)|ja|天白川 (愛知県)|qq=draft|qq=draft}} - A river flowing through {{ill|Nisshin|ja|日進市|qq=draft|qq=draft}} and {{ill|Nagoya|ja|名古屋市|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, named after a shrine to Tenpaku deity in its lower reaches. * {{ill|Tenpaku Ward|ja|天白区|qq=draft|qq=draft}} - A ward of Nagoya named after the river. * {{ill|Tenpaku Village (Aichi)|ja|天白村 (愛知県)|qq=draft|qq=draft}} - Formerly in Nagoya, named after the river. * Tenpaku River - A small river in {{ill|Higashiura Town|ja|東浦町|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, also associated with the Tenpaku deity.<ref>{{Cite book|和書|title=張州府志 第6|year=1916|publisher=名古屋史談会}}</ref> * {{ill|Tenpaku Town (Okazaki)|ja|天白町 (岡崎市)|qq=draft|qq=draft}} - A town in {{ill|Okazaki|ja|岡崎市|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, named after the Tenpaku deity. * {{ill|Tenpaku River (Tahara)|ja|天白川 (田原市)|qq=draft|qq=draft}} - A river flowing through {{ill|Tahara City|ja|田原市|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.
=== Mie Prefecture === * {{ill|Tenpaku River (Mie)|ja|天白川 (三重県)|qq=draft|qq=draft}} - A river in {{ill|Yokkaichi|ja|四日市市|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. * {{ill|Tenpaku Village (Mie)|ja|天白村 (三重県)|qq=draft|qq=draft}} - Formerly part of {{ill|Matsusaka|ja|松阪市|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.
