[[sn:Tenpaku faith]]
[[en:Tenpaku faith]]
[[ja:天白信仰]]
[[sn:enpaku faith]]

'''Tenpaku Faith''' (天白信仰) is a form of {{ill|folk religion|ja|民間信仰|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/folk religion|qq=}} found primarily in the eastern half of {{ill|Honshu|lt=Honshu|lt=Honshū|ja|本州|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Honshū|qq=}}. Its distribution centers on {{ill|Nagano Prefecture|ja|長野県|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nagano Prefecture|qq=}} and {{ill|Shizuoka Prefecture|ja|静岡県|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shizuoka Prefecture|qq=}}, extending southward to the Nansei and Shima regions of {{ill|Mie Prefecture|ja|三重県|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Mie Prefecture|qq=}} and northward to {{ill|Iwate Prefecture|ja|岩手県|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Iwate Prefecture|qq=}}.

Due to the diverse associations with {{ill|star deities|ja|星神|1=Worship of heavenly bodies|2=ja|3=星神|lt=Star deities|1=Worship of heavenly bodies|2=ja|3=星神|lt=Star deities|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/star deities|13=User:Immanuelle/Worship of heavenly bodies|qq=}}, [[Suijin|water gods]], and prayers for safe childbirth, various studies and interpretations have been conducted. Since the 1980s, the faith has often been linked to the ancestral deity of the {{ill|Asami clan|ja|麻積氏|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Asami clan|qq=}}, Tenpakuhahajin (天白羽神, also known as {{ill|Nagashirahano no Kami|lt=Nagashirahano no Kami|lt=Nagashirahahajin|ja|長白羽神|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nagashirahahajin|qq=}}), worshipped at the {{ill|Hatadono Shrines|lt=Hatadono Shrines|lt=Hashiro Shrine|ja|機殿神社|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hashiro Shrine|qq=}} in the ancient province of Ise.

== History of Research ==
Shun'ichirō Mitoshi noted that the earliest studies on Tenpaku faith date back to the {{ill|Edo period|ja|江戸時代|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Edo period|qq=}}. In the linguistic dictionary *Wakun no Shiori* compiled by {{ill|Tanikawa Kotosuga|ja|谷川士清|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tanikawa Kotosuga|qq=}}, there is a reference to "numerous shrines in Ise Province called Tenpaku Daimyōjin, though their exact nature is unclear." Similarly, *Chōshū Fushi* mentions the Tenpaku Shrine in Ōya Village (now {{ill|Ōya Town|ja|大矢町|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ōya Town|qq=}} in {{ill|Inazawa City|ja|稲沢市|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Inazawa City|qq=}}, {{ill|Aichi Prefecture|ja|愛知県|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Aichi Prefecture|qq=}}), suggesting it was dedicated to {{ill|Venus|ja|金星|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Venus|qq=}}, referred to as Taibakusei (太白星). In 1862, Takahira Nakamura theorized in *Suruga Shiryō* that the deity might represent a synthesis of Tianyi (天一) and Taibai (太白) deities.

In 1909, the folklorist {{ill|Yanagita Kunio|ja|柳田國男|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yanagita Kunio|qq=}} explored Tenpaku in *Life of the Mountain People*. In subsequent works, he dismissed earlier speculative theories, proposing that Tenpaku was likely connected to {{ill|Fūjin|lt=Fūjin|lt=Wind deities|ja|風神|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/wind deities|qq=}}. This theory gained significant attention among later scholars.

From the post-World War II period, research on Tenpaku progressed. {{ill|Yoshio Horita|ja|堀田吉雄|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yoshio Horita|qq=}}, a disciple of Yanagita, published several studies between 1951 and 1964. While he leaned toward the theory of Tenpaku being a fusion of Chinese deities Tianyi and Taibai, he remained cautious, awaiting further evidence.

In 1971, Nokiku Imai compiled a detailed map of Tenpaku shrines in *Great Tenpaku Kami*, asserting that the faith predates wet-rice cultivation and reaches back to the {{ill|Jōmon period|ja|縄文時代|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Jōmon period|qq=}}. The publication also included analyses suggesting connections to {{ill|flood control|ja|風水害|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/flood control|qq=}}, Tibetan Lamaist sexual symbolism, and the deity Tenpakuhahajin.

Building on Imai's research, Sōmoku Yamada conducted in-depth surveys in five prefectures (Mie, Aichi, Nagano, Shizuoka, and Yamanashi), which he serialized as *Tenpaku Chronicles* in 1977. He proposed that Tenpaku's origins lie in the deity Tenpakuhahajin.

