[[ja:天白信仰]]
[[sn:enpaku faith]]

'''Tenpaku Faith''' (天白信仰) is a form of [[:en:Folk religion|folk religion]] found primarily in the eastern half of [[:en:Honshu|Honshū]]. Its distribution centers on [[:en:Nagano Prefecture|Nagano Prefecture]] and [[:en:Shizuoka Prefecture|Shizuoka Prefecture]], extending southward to the Nansei and Shima regions of [[:en:Mie Prefecture|Mie Prefecture]] and northward to [[:en:Iwate Prefecture|Iwate Prefecture]].

Due to the diverse associations with {{ill|star deities|ja|星神|1=Worship of heavenly bodies|2=ja|3=星神|lt=Star deities|1=Worship of heavenly bodies|2=ja|3=星神|lt=Star deities|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/star deities|13=User:Immanuelle/Worship of heavenly bodies|qq=}}, [[Suijin|water gods]], and prayers for safe childbirth, various studies and interpretations have been conducted. Since the 1980s, the faith has often been linked to the ancestral deity of the {{ill|Asami clan|ja|麻積氏|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Asami clan|qq=}}, Tenpakuhahajin (天白羽神, also known as {{ill|Nagashirahano no Kami|lt=Nagashirahano no Kami|lt=Nagashirahahajin|ja|長白羽神|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nagashirahahajin|qq=}}), worshipped at the {{ill|Hatadono Shrines|lt=Hatadono Shrines|lt=Hashiro Shrine|ja|機殿神社|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hashiro Shrine|qq=}} in the ancient province of Ise.

== History of Research ==
Shun'ichirō Mitoshi noted that the earliest studies on Tenpaku faith date back to the [[:en:Edo period|Edo period]]. In the linguistic dictionary *Wakun no Shiori* compiled by [[:en:Tanikawa Kotosuga|Tanikawa Kotosuga]], there is a reference to "numerous shrines in Ise Province called Tenpaku Daimyōjin, though their exact nature is unclear." Similarly, *Chōshū Fushi* mentions the Tenpaku Shrine in Ōya Village (now {{ill|Ōya Town|ja|大矢町|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ōya Town|qq=}} in [[:en:Inazawa|Inazawa City]], [[:en:Aichi Prefecture|Aichi Prefecture]]), suggesting it was dedicated to [[:en:Venus|Venus]], referred to as Taibakusei (太白星). In 1862, Takahira Nakamura theorized in *Suruga Shiryō* that the deity might represent a synthesis of Tianyi (天一) and Taibai (太白) deities.

In 1909, the folklorist [[:en:Kunio Yanagita|Yanagita Kunio]] explored Tenpaku in *Life of the Mountain People*. In subsequent works, he dismissed earlier speculative theories, proposing that Tenpaku was likely connected to [[:en:Fūjin|Wind deities]]. This theory gained significant attention among later scholars.

From the post-World War II period, research on Tenpaku progressed. {{ill|Yoshio Horita|ja|堀田吉雄|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yoshio Horita|qq=}}, a disciple of Yanagita, published several studies between 1951 and 1964. While he leaned toward the theory of Tenpaku being a fusion of Chinese deities Tianyi and Taibai, he remained cautious, awaiting further evidence.

In 1971, Nokiku Imai compiled a detailed map of Tenpaku shrines in *Great Tenpaku Kami*, asserting that the faith predates wet-rice cultivation and reaches back to the [[:en:Jōmon period|Jōmon period]]. The publication also included analyses suggesting connections to {{ill|flood control|ja|風水害|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/flood control|qq=}}, Tibetan Lamaist sexual symbolism, and the deity Tenpakuhahajin.

Building on Imai's research, Sōmoku Yamada conducted in-depth surveys in five prefectures (Mie, Aichi, Nagano, Shizuoka, and Yamanashi), which he serialized as *Tenpaku Chronicles* in 1977. He proposed that Tenpaku's origins lie in the deity Tenpakuhahajin.

