From the post-World War II period, research on Tenpaku progressed. {{ill|Yoshio Horita|ja|堀田吉雄|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yoshio Horita|qq=|1=Yoshio Hotta|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q56348851}}, a disciple of Yanagita, published several studies between 1951 and 1964. While he leaned toward the theory of Tenpaku being a fusion of Chinese deities Tianyi and Taibai, he remained cautious, awaiting further evidence.
In 1971, Nokiku Imai compiled a detailed map of Tenpaku shrines in *Great Tenpaku Kami*, asserting that the faith predates wet-rice cultivation and reaches back to the [[:en:Jōmon period|Jōmon period]]. The publication also included analyses suggesting connections to {{ill|flood control|ja|風水害|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/flood control|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 自然災害|1=natural disaster|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q8065}}, Tibetan Lamaist sexual symbolism, and the deity Tenpakuhahajin.
Building on Imai's research, Sōmoku Yamada conducted in-depth surveys in five prefectures (Mie, Aichi, Nagano, Shizuoka, and Yamanashi), which he serialized as *Tenpaku Chronicles* in 1977. He proposed that Tenpaku's origins lie in the deity Tenpakuhahajin.
== Places Associated with Tenpaku == {{Seealso|{{ill|Tenpaku|ja|天白|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tenpaku|qq=}}}} === Aichi Prefecture === * {{ill|Tenpaku River (Aichi)|ja|天白川 (愛知県)|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tenpaku River (Aichi)|qq=|1=Tenpaku River|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q11443111}} - A river flowing through [[:en:Nisshin, Aichi|Nisshin]] and [[:en:Nagoya|Nagoya]], named after a shrine to Tenpaku deity in its lower reaches. * [[:en:Tenpaku-ku|Tenpaku Ward]] - A ward of Nagoya named after the river. * {{ill|Tenpaku Village (Aichi)|ja|天白村 (愛知県)|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tenpaku Village (Aichi)|qq=|1=Tenpaku|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q17177017}} - Formerly in Nagoya, named after the river. * Tenpaku River - A small river in [[:en:Higashiura|Higashiura Town]], also associated with the Tenpaku deity.<ref>{{Cite book|和書|title=張州府志 第6|year=1916|publisher=名古屋史談会}}</ref> * {{ill|Tenpaku Town (Okazaki)|ja|天白町 (岡崎市)|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tenpaku Town (Okazaki)|qq=|1=Tenpaku-chō, Okazaki|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q17218861}} - A town in [[:en:Okazaki, Aichi|Okazaki]], named after the Tenpaku deity. * {{ill|Tenpaku River (Tahara)|ja|天白川 (田原市)|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tenpaku River (Tahara)|qq=|1=Tenpaku River|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q132044415}} - A river flowing through [[:en:Tahara, Aichi|Tahara City]].
=== Mie Prefecture === * {{ill|Tenpaku River (Mie)|ja|天白川 (三重県)|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tenpaku River (Mie)|qq=|1=Tenpaku River|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q17174431}} - A river in [[:en:Yokkaichi|Yokkaichi]]. * {{ill|Tenpaku Village (Mie)|ja|天白村 (三重県)|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tenpaku Village (Mie)|qq=|1=Tenpaku|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q17175728}} - Formerly part of [[:en:Matsusaka|Matsusaka]].
